Trump and the Economy
New York — Financial markets finally woke up to the fact that Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured two years of Trump's unchecked tweets and public statements, and the obvious question is, what has kept this going for so long?
On one hand, so far investors have been treating Trump as a thunderous but rainless figure.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies favorable to the corporate sector and shareholders, they are willing to grant him the benefit of the doubt.
Many people believed that, in the end, "the adults in the room" would rein in Trump and ensure that government policies remained within bounds.
This assumption was largely confirmed during Trump's first year in office, a period during which economic growth and expectations of corporate profit growth — thanks to the upcoming tax cuts and deregulation — led to a strong stock market performance.
In 2017, U.S. stock indices rose by more than 20%.
But in 2018, the situation turned sharply downward, especially in the last few months.
Although corporate profits increased by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the U.S. stock market fluctuated throughout most of the year and then experienced a sharp decline.
Currently, various indices are in a correction range (i.e., down 10% from their most recent highs), with technology stock indices (such as the NASDAQ) having fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Although increased market volatility reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turbulence is due to Trump.
At the beginning of the year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which pushed up long-term interest rates and pushed an economy already near full employment to its peak.
By February, concerns about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% led to the first flight-to-safety episode of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other major U.S. trading partners.
Concerns about government protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year, but are now reaching a new peak.
The United States' recent actions toward China seem to be preparing for a full-scale trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies could lead to stagflation (weakened growth and increased inflation).
After all, Trump is prepared to limit foreign direct investment inflows and has implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will hinder the growth of labor supply in the context of an aging workforce and increasing skill mismatches.
Furthermore, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure plan to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other occasions, Trump continuously criticized corporate behaviors such as hiring, production, investment, and pricing, especially targeting tech companies, which have already faced widespread opposition and intensifying competition from Chinese counterparts.
Emerging markets were also impacted by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening raised both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies experienced capital flight and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports suffered losses due to falling commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade ties with China felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policies created volatility.
The U.S. reimposing sanctions on Iran raised oil prices, and afterward, the U.S. government revoked exemptions and pressured Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, leading to a sharp drop in oil prices.
Although American consumers benefited from low oil prices, the stock prices of U.S. energy companies could not withstand the impact.
In addition, excessive oil price volatility is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hinders sound investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, now it is clear that almost all the benefits from last year's tax cuts have flowed to the corporate sector, rather than in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages to households.
This means that household consumption may soon slow down, further affecting the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent quarter's sharp drop in U.S. and global stock markets was Trump's own remarks and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (although he recently reached a "truce" with Chinese President Xi Jinping) was Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve. His criticism began in the spring of 2018, when the U.S. economic growth rate was above 4%.
Due to these earlier criticisms, the market became skittish when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates this month, while also signaling that it would raise rates more slowly in 2019.
More likely, the Fed's relatively hawkish stance was a reaction to Trump's criticism of it.
Facing an antagonistic president's tweets, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needs to send a signal that the central bank remains politically independent.
But then, because Congress refused to fund his useless border wall with Mexico, Trump decided to shut down part of the federal government.
This move put the market into a state of near panic, and soon reports emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could turn a market correction into a crash.
Just before the Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to calm the market.
He claimed that Trump had no plan to fire Powell, and that the U.S. fiscal situation was good — but this precisely highlighted the question of whether the situation was really good.
Internal personnel changes within the government, which may not directly affect economic decisions, have recently caused market concerns.
The White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave, and the Trump cabinet will no longer have sane individuals.
The remaining members will all be economic nationalists and hawkish foreign policy advocates, who will follow Trump blindly.
Currently, the possibility of a comprehensive geopolitical conflict with China cannot be ruled out.
A new cold war is likely to lead to deglobalization and disrupt global supply chains, but the technology sector will be hit first, as evidenced by the recent cases of ZTE and Huawei.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO during a time of economic and political instability in Europe.
The special prosecutor Robert Mueller's investigation into the relationship between Trump's 2016 campaign and Russia is the sword of Damocles hanging over Trump's presidency.
Trump is now the Dr. Strangelove of financial markets.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in a mutually assured economic destruction.
Now, the market sees this danger, and the risks of financial crisis and global recession are rising steadily.
